0:00:,000 --> 0:00:07,000
Translator: Jenny Zurawell

2
0:00:15.26,000 --> 0:00:17,000
A few months ago

3
0:00:17.26,000 --> 0:00:19,000
the Nobel Prize in physics

4
0:00:19.26,000 --> 0:00:21,000
was awarded to two teams of astronomers

5
0:00:21.26,000 --> 0:00:24,000
for a discovery that has been hailed

6
0:00:24.26,000 --> 0:00:26,000
as one of the most important

7
0:00:26.26,000 --> 0:00:28,000
astronomical observations ever.

8
0:00:28.26,000 --> 0:00:3,000
And today, after briefly describing what they found,

9
0:00:30.26,000 --> 0:00:33,000
I'm going to tell you about a highly controversial framework

10
0:00:33.26,000 --> 0:00:36,000
for explaining their discovery,

11
0:00:36.26,000 --> 0:00:38,000
namely the possibility

12
0:00:38.26,000 --> 0:00:4,000
that way beyond the Earth,

13
0:00:40.26,000 --> 0:00:43,000
the Milky Way and other distant galaxies,

14
0:00:43.26,000 --> 0:00:45,000
we may find that our universe

15
0:00:45.26,000 --> 0:00:47,000
is not the only universe,

16
0:00:47.26,000 --> 0:00:49,000
but is instead

17
0:00:49.26,000 --> 0:00:51,000
part of a vast complex of universes

18
0:00:51.26,000 --> 0:00:53,000
that we call the multiverse.

19
0:00:53.26,000 --> 0:00:56,000
Now the idea of a multiverse is a strange one.

20
0:00:56.26,000 --> 0:00:58,000
I mean, most of us were raised to believe

21
0:00:58.26,000 --> 0:01:01,000
that the word "universe" means everything.

22
0:01:01.26,000 --> 0:01:04,000
And I say most of us with forethought,

23
0:01:04.26,000 --> 0:01:07,000
as my four-year-old daughter has heard me speak of these ideas since she was born.

24
0:01:07.26,000 --> 0:01:09,000
And last year I was holding her

25
0:01:09.26,000 --> 0:01:11,000
and I said, "Sophia,

26
0:01:11.26,000 --> 0:01:14,000
I love you more than anything in the universe."

27
0:01:14.26,000 --> 0:01:16,000
And she turned to me and said, "Daddy,

28
0:01:16.26,000 --> 0:01:18,000
universe or multiverse?"

29
0:01:18.26,000 --> 0:01:21,000
(Laughter)

30
0:01:21.26,000 --> 0:01:24,000
But barring such an anomalous upbringing,

31
0:01:24.26,000 --> 0:01:26,000
it is strange to imagine

32
0:01:26.26,000 --> 0:01:28,000
other realms separate from ours,

33
0:01:28.26,000 --> 0:01:3,000
most with fundamentally different features,

34
0:01:30.26,000 --> 0:01:33,000
that would rightly be called universes of their own.

35
0:01:33.26,000 --> 0:01:35,000
And yet,

36
0:01:35.26,000 --> 0:01:37,000
speculative though the idea surely is,

37
0:01:37.26,000 --> 0:01:39,000
I aim to convince you

38
0:01:39.26,000 --> 0:01:41,000
that there's reason for taking it seriously,

39
0:01:41.26,000 --> 0:01:43,000
as it just might be right.

40
0:01:43.26,000 --> 0:01:46,000
I'm going to tell the story of the multiverse in three parts.

41
0:01:46.26,000 --> 0:01:48,000
In part one,

42
0:01:48.26,000 --> 0:01:5,000
I'm going to describe those Nobel Prize-winning results

43
0:01:50.26,000 --> 0:01:52,000
and to highlight a profound mystery

44
0:01:52.26,000 --> 0:01:54,000
which those results revealed.

45
0:01:54.26,000 --> 0:01:56,000
In part two,

46
0:01:56.26,000 --> 0:01:58,000
I'll offer a solution to that mystery.

47
0:01:58.26,000 --> 0:02:,000
It's based on an approach called string theory,

48
0:02:00.26,000 --> 0:02:02,000
and that's where the idea of the multiverse

49
0:02:02.26,000 --> 0:02:04,000
will come into the story.

50
0:02:04.26,000 --> 0:02:06,000
Finally, in part three,

51
0:02:06.26,000 --> 0:02:08,000
I'm going to describe a cosmological theory

52
0:02:08.26,000 --> 0:02:1,000
called inflation,

53
0:02:10.26,000 --> 0:02:13,000
which will pull all the pieces of the story together.

54
0:02:13.26,000 --> 0:02:17,000
Okay, part one starts back in 1929

55
0:02:17.26,000 --> 0:02:19,000
when the great astronomer Edwin Hubble

56
0:02:19.26,000 --> 0:02:22,000
realized that the distant galaxies

57
0:02:22.26,000 --> 0:02:24,000
were all rushing away from us,

58
0:02:24.26,000 --> 0:02:26,000
establishing that space itself is stretching,

59
0:02:26.26,000 --> 0:02:28,000
it's expanding.

60
0:02:28.26,000 --> 0:02:31,000
Now this was revolutionary.

61
0:02:31.26,000 --> 0:02:34,000
The prevailing wisdom was that on the largest of scales

62
0:02:34.26,000 --> 0:02:36,000
the universe was static.

63
0:02:36.26,000 --> 0:02:38,000
But even so,

64
0:02:38.26,000 --> 0:02:41,000
there was one thing that everyone was certain of:

65
0:02:41.26,000 --> 0:02:44,000
The expansion must be slowing down.

66
0:02:44.26,000 --> 0:02:47,000
That, much as the gravitational pull of the Earth

67
0:02:47.26,000 --> 0:02:5,000
slows the ascent of an apple tossed upward,

68
0:02:50.26,000 --> 0:02:52,000
the gravitational pull

69
0:02:52.26,000 --> 0:02:54,000
of each galaxy on every other

70
0:02:54.26,000 --> 0:02:56,000
must be slowing

71
0:02:56.26,000 --> 0:02:58,000
the expansion of space.

72
0:02:58.26,000 --> 0:03:01,000
Now let's fast-forward to the 1990s

73
0:03:01.26,000 --> 0:03:03,000
when those two teams of astronomers

74
0:03:03.26,000 --> 0:03:05,000
I mentioned at the outset

75
0:03:05.26,000 --> 0:03:07,000
were inspired by this reasoning

76
0:03:07.26,000 --> 0:03:09,000
to measure the rate

77
0:03:09.26,000 --> 0:03:11,000
at which the expansion has been slowing.

78
0:03:11.26,000 --> 0:03:13,000
And they did this

79
0:03:13.26,000 --> 0:03:15,000
by painstaking observations

80
0:03:15.26,000 --> 0:03:17,000
of numerous distant galaxies,

81
0:03:17.26,000 --> 0:03:19,000
allowing them to chart

82
0:03:19.26,000 --> 0:03:22,000
how the expansion rate has changed over time.

83
0:03:22.26,000 --> 0:03:25,000
Here's the surprise:

84
0:03:25.26,000 --> 0:03:28,000
They found that the expansion is not slowing down.

85
0:03:28.26,000 --> 0:03:3,000
Instead they found that it's speeding up,

86
0:03:30.26,000 --> 0:03:32,000
going faster and faster.

87
0:03:32.26,000 --> 0:03:34,000
That's like tossing an apple upward

88
0:03:34.26,000 --> 0:03:36,000
and it goes up faster and faster.

89
0:03:36.26,000 --> 0:03:38,000
Now if you saw an apple do that,

90
0:03:38.26,000 --> 0:03:4,000
you'd want to know why.

91
0:03:40.26,000 --> 0:03:42,000
What's pushing on it?

92
0:03:42.26,000 --> 0:03:44,000
Similarly, the astronomers' results

93
0:03:44.26,000 --> 0:03:47,000
are surely well-deserving of the Nobel Prize,

94
0:03:47.26,000 --> 0:03:51,000
but they raised an analogous question.

95
0:03:51.26,000 --> 0:03:53,000
What force is driving all galaxies

96
0:03:53.26,000 --> 0:03:56,000
to rush away from every other

97
0:03:56.26,000 --> 0:03:59,000
at an ever-quickening speed?

98
0:03:59.26,000 --> 0:04:01,000
Well the most promising answer

99
0:04:01.26,000 --> 0:04:04,000
comes from an old idea of Einstein's.

100
0:04:04.26,000 --> 0:04:06,000
You see, we are all used to gravity

101
0:04:06.26,000 --> 0:04:09,000
being a force that does one thing,

102
0:04:09.26,000 --> 0:04:11,000
pulls objects together.

103
0:04:11.26,000 --> 0:04:13,000
But in Einstein's theory of gravity,

104
0:04:13.26,000 --> 0:04:15,000
his general theory of relativity,

105
0:04:15.26,000 --> 0:04:18,000
gravity can also push things apart.

106
0:04:18.26,000 --> 0:04:21,000
How? Well according to Einstein's math,

107
0:04:21.26,000 --> 0:04:23,000
if space is uniformly filled

108
0:04:23.26,000 --> 0:04:25,000
with an invisible energy,

109
0:04:25.26,000 --> 0:04:28,000
sort of like a uniform, invisible mist,

110
0:04:28.26,000 --> 0:04:31,000
then the gravity generated by that mist

111
0:04:31.26,000 --> 0:04:33,000
would be repulsive,

112
0:04:33.26,000 --> 0:04:35,000
repulsive gravity,

113
0:04:35.26,000 --> 0:04:38,000
which is just what we need to explain the observations.

114
0:04:38.26,000 --> 0:04:4,000
Because the repulsive gravity

115
0:04:40.26,000 --> 0:04:42,000
of an invisible energy in space --

116
0:04:42.26,000 --> 0:04:44,000
we now call it dark energy,

117
0:04:44.26,000 --> 0:04:47,000
but I've made it smokey white here so you can see it --

118
0:04:47.26,000 --> 0:04:49,000
its repulsive gravity

119
0:04:49.26,000 --> 0:04:51,000
would cause each galaxy to push against every other,

120
0:04:51.26,000 --> 0:04:53,000
driving expansion to speed up,

121
0:04:53.26,000 --> 0:04:55,000
not slow down.

122
0:04:55.26,000 --> 0:04:57,000
And this explanation

123
0:04:57.26,000 --> 0:04:59,000
represents great progress.

124
0:04:59.26,000 --> 0:05:02,000
But I promised you a mystery

125
0:05:02.26,000 --> 0:05:04,000
here in part one.

126
0:05:04.26,000 --> 0:05:06,000
Here it is.

127
0:05:06.26,000 --> 0:05:08,000
When the astronomers worked out

128
0:05:08.26,000 --> 0:05:11,000
