0:10:45.26,000 --> 0:10:47,000
and in particular,

264
0:10:47.26,000 --> 0:10:49,000
the amount of dark energy in each universe

265
0:10:49.26,000 --> 0:10:51,000
will be different.

266
0:10:51.26,000 --> 0:10:53,000
Which means that the mystery

267
0:10:53.26,000 --> 0:10:55,000
of explaining the amount of dark energy we've now measured

268
0:10:55.26,000 --> 0:10:58,000
would take on a wholly different character.

269
0:10:58.26,000 --> 0:11:,000
In this context,

270
0:11:00.26,000 --> 0:11:03,000
the laws of physics can't explain one number for the dark energy

271
0:11:03.26,000 --> 0:11:06,000
because there isn't just one number,

272
0:11:06.26,000 --> 0:11:08,000
there are many numbers.

273
0:11:08.26,000 --> 0:11:1,000
Which means

274
0:11:10.26,000 --> 0:11:13,000
we have been asking the wrong question.

275
0:11:13.26,000 --> 0:11:15,000
It's that the right question to ask is,

276
0:11:15.26,000 --> 0:11:18,000
why do we humans find ourselves in a universe

277
0:11:18.26,000 --> 0:11:21,000
with a particular amount of dark energy we've measured

278
0:11:21.26,000 --> 0:11:24,000
instead of any of the other possibilities

279
0:11:24.26,000 --> 0:11:26,000
that are out there?

280
0:11:26.26,000 --> 0:11:29,000
And that's a question on which we can make headway.

281
0:11:29.26,000 --> 0:11:31,000
Because those universes

282
0:11:31.26,000 --> 0:11:33,000
that have much more dark energy than ours,

283
0:11:33.26,000 --> 0:11:36,000
whenever matter tries to clump into galaxies,

284
0:11:36.26,000 --> 0:11:39,000
the repulsive push of the dark energy is so strong

285
0:11:39.26,000 --> 0:11:41,000
that it blows the clump apart

286
0:11:41.26,000 --> 0:11:43,000
and galaxies don't form.

287
0:11:43.26,000 --> 0:11:46,000
And in those universes that have much less dark energy,

288
0:11:46.26,000 --> 0:11:48,000
well they collapse back on themselves so quickly

289
0:11:48.26,000 --> 0:11:51,000
that, again, galaxies don't form.

290
0:11:51.26,000 --> 0:11:54,000
And without galaxies, there are no stars, no planets

291
0:11:54.26,000 --> 0:11:56,000
and no chance

292
0:11:56.26,000 --> 0:11:58,000
for our form of life

293
0:11:58.26,000 --> 0:12:,000
to exist in those other universes.

294
0:12:00.26,000 --> 0:12:02,000
So we find ourselves in a universe

295
0:12:02.26,000 --> 0:12:05,000
with the particular amount of dark energy we've measured

296
0:12:05.26,000 --> 0:12:08,000
simply because our universe has conditions

297
0:12:08.26,000 --> 0:12:12,000
hospitable to our form of life.

298
0:12:12.26,000 --> 0:12:14,000
And that would be that.

299
0:12:14.26,000 --> 0:12:16,000
Mystery solved,

300
0:12:16.26,000 --> 0:12:18,000
multiverse found.

301
0:12:18.26,000 --> 0:12:23,000
Now some find this explanation unsatisfying.

302
0:12:23.26,000 --> 0:12:25,000
We're used to physics

303
0:12:25.26,000 --> 0:12:28,000
giving us definitive explanations for the features we observe.

304
0:12:28.26,000 --> 0:12:3,000
But the point is,

305
0:12:30.26,000 --> 0:12:33,000
if the feature you're observing

306
0:12:33.26,000 --> 0:12:35,000
can and does take on

307
0:12:35.26,000 --> 0:12:37,000
a wide variety of different values

308
0:12:37.26,000 --> 0:12:4,000
across the wider landscape of reality,

309
0:12:40.26,000 --> 0:12:42,000
then thinking one explanation

310
0:12:42.26,000 --> 0:12:44,000
for a particular value

311
0:12:44.26,000 --> 0:12:47,000
is simply misguided.

312
0:12:47.26,000 --> 0:12:49,000
An early example

313
0:12:49.26,000 --> 0:12:52,000
comes from the great astronomer Johannes Kepler

314
0:12:52.26,000 --> 0:12:54,000
who was obsessed with understanding

315
0:12:54.26,000 --> 0:12:56,000
a different number --

316
0:12:56.26,000 --> 0:13:,000
why the Sun is 93 million miles away from the Earth.

317
0:13:00.26,000 --> 0:13:03,000
And he worked for decades trying to explain this number,

318
0:13:03.26,000 --> 0:13:06,000
but he never succeeded, and we know why.

319
0:13:06.26,000 --> 0:13:08,000
Kepler was asking

320
0:13:08.26,000 --> 0:13:1,000
the wrong question.

321
0:13:10.26,000 --> 0:13:13,000
We now know that there are many planets

322
0:13:13.26,000 --> 0:13:16,000
at a wide variety of different distances from their host stars.

323
0:13:16.26,000 --> 0:13:19,000
So hoping that the laws of physics

324
0:13:19.26,000 --> 0:13:22,000
will explain one particular number, 93 million miles,

325
0:13:22.26,000 --> 0:13:25,000
well that is simply wrongheaded.

326
0:13:25.26,000 --> 0:13:27,000
Instead the right question to ask is,

327
0:13:27.26,000 --> 0:13:3,000
why do we humans find ourselves on a planet

328
0:13:30.26,000 --> 0:13:32,000
at this particular distance,

329
0:13:32.26,000 --> 0:13:35,000
instead of any of the other possibilities?

330
0:13:35.26,000 --> 0:13:38,000
And again, that's a question we can answer.

331
0:13:38.26,000 --> 0:13:41,000
Those planets which are much closer to a star like the Sun

332
0:13:41.26,000 --> 0:13:43,000
would be so hot

333
0:13:43.26,000 --> 0:13:45,000
that our form of life wouldn't exist.

334
0:13:45.26,000 --> 0:13:48,000
And those planets that are much farther away from the star,

335
0:13:48.26,000 --> 0:13:5,000
well they're so cold

336
0:13:50.26,000 --> 0:13:52,000
that, again, our form of life would not take hold.

337
0:13:52.26,000 --> 0:13:54,000
So we find ourselves

338
0:13:54.26,000 --> 0:13:56,000
on a planet at this particular distance

339
0:13:56.26,000 --> 0:13:58,000
simply because it yields conditions

340
0:13:58.26,000 --> 0:14:01,000
vital to our form of life.

341
0:14:01.26,000 --> 0:14:04,000
And when it comes to planets and their distances,

342
0:14:04.26,000 --> 0:14:08,000
this clearly is the right kind of reasoning.

343
0:14:08.26,000 --> 0:14:1,000
The point is,

344
0:14:10.26,000 --> 0:14:13,000
when it comes to universes and the dark energy that they contain,

345
0:14:13.26,000 --> 0:14:17,000
it may also be the right kind of reasoning.

346
0:14:17.26,000 --> 0:14:2,000
One key difference, of course,

347
0:14:20.26,000 --> 0:14:22,000
is we know that there are other planets out there,

348
0:14:22.26,000 --> 0:14:25,000
but so far I've only speculated on the possibility

349
0:14:25.26,000 --> 0:14:27,000
that there might be other universes.

350
0:14:27.26,000 --> 0:14:29,000
So to pull it all together,

351
0:14:29.26,000 --> 0:14:31,000
we need a mechanism

352
0:14:31.26,000 --> 0:14:34,000
that can actually generate other universes.

353
0:14:34.26,000 --> 0:14:37,000
And that takes me to my final part, part three.

354
0:14:37.26,000 --> 0:14:4,000
Because such a mechanism has been found

355
0:14:40.26,000 --> 0:14:43,000
by cosmologists trying to understand the Big Bang.

356
0:14:43.26,000 --> 0:14:45,000
You see, when we speak of the Big Bang,

357
0:14:45.26,000 --> 0:14:47,000
we often have an image

358
0:14:47.26,000 --> 0:14:49,000
of a kind of cosmic explosion

359
0:14:49.26,000 --> 0:14:51,000
that created our universe

360
0:14:51.26,000 --> 0:14:54,000
and set space rushing outward.

361
0:14:54.26,000 --> 0:14:56,000
But there's a little secret.

362
0:14:56.26,000 --> 0:14:59,000
The Big Bang leaves out something pretty important,

363
0:14:59.26,000 --> 0:15:01,000
the Bang.

364
0:15:01.26,000 --> 0:15:04,000
It tells us how the universe evolved after the Bang,

365
0:15:04.26,000 --> 0:15:06,000
but gives us no insight

366
0:15:06.26,000 --> 0:15:1,000
into what would have powered the Bang itself.

367
0:15:10.26,000 --> 0:15:12,000
And this gap was finally filled

368
0:15:12.26,000 --> 0:15:14,000
by an enhanced version of the Big Bang theory.

369
0:15:14.26,000 --> 0:15:17,000
It's called inflationary cosmology,

370
0:15:17.26,000 --> 0:15:21,000
which identified a particular kind of fuel

371
0:15:21.26,000 --> 0:15:23,000
that would naturally generate

372
0:15:23.26,000 --> 0:15:25,000
an outward rush of space.

373
0:15:25.26,000 --> 0:15:28,000
The fuel is based on something called a quantum field,

374
0:15:28.26,000 --> 0:15:31,000
but the only detail that matters for us

375
0:15:31.26,000 --> 0:15:34,000
is that this fuel proves to be so efficient

376
0:15:34.26,000 --> 0:15:36,000
that it's virtually impossible

377
0:15:36.26,000 --> 0:15:38,000
to use it all up,

378
0:15:38.26,000 --> 0:15:4,000
which means in the inflationary theory,

379
0:15:40.26,000 --> 0:15:43,000
the Big Bang giving rise to our universe

380
0:15:43.26,000 --> 0:15:46,000
is likely not a one-time event.

381
0:15:46.26,000 --> 0:15:49,000
Instead the fuel not only generated our Big Bang,

382
0:15:49.26,000 --> 0:15:55,000
but it would also generate countless other Big Bangs,

383
0:15:55.26,000 --> 0:15:58,000
each giving rise to its own separate universe

384
0:15:58.26,000 --> 0:16:,000
with our universe becoming but one bubble

385
0:16:00.26,000 --> 0:16:03,000
in a grand cosmic bubble bath of universes.

386
0:16:03.26,000 --> 0:16:05,000
And now, when we meld this with string theory,

387
0:16:05.26,000 --> 0:16:07,000
here's the picture we're led to.

388
0:16:07.26,000 --> 0:16:09,000
Each of these universes has extra dimensions.

389
0:16:09.26,000 --> 0:16:12,000
The extra dimensions take on a wide variety of different shapes.

390
0:16:12.26,000 --> 0:16:15,000
The different shapes yield different physical features.

391
0:16:15.26,000 --> 0:16:18,000
And we find ourselves in one universe instead of another

392
0:16:18.26,000 --> 0:16:21,000
simply because it's only in our universe

393
0:16:21.26,000 --> 0:16:24,000
that the physical features, like the amount of dark energy,

394
0:16:24.26,000 --> 0:16:28,000
are right for our form of life to take hold.

395
0:16:28.26,000 --> 0:16:31,000
And this is the compelling but highly controversial picture

396
0:16:31.26,000 --> 0:16:33,000
of the wider cosmos

397
0:16:33.26,000 --> 0:16:35,000
that cutting-edge observation and theory

398
0:16:35.26,000 --> 0:16:39,000
have now led us to seriously consider.

399
0:16:39.26,000 --> 0:16:43,000
One big remaining question, of course, is,

400
0:16:43.26,000 --> 0:16:46,000
could we ever confirm

401
0:16:46.26,000 --> 0:16:49,000
the existence of other universes?

402
0:16:49.26,000 --> 0:16:51,000
Well let me describe

403
0:16:51.26,000 --> 0:16:54,000
one way that might one day happen.

404
0:16:54.26,000 --> 0:16:56,000
The inflationary theory

405
0:16:56.26,000 --> 0:16:58,000
already has strong observational support.

406
0:16:58.26,000 --> 0:17:,000
Because the theory predicts

407
0:17:00.26,000 --> 0:17:02,000
that the Big Bang would have been so intense

408
0:17:02.26,000 --> 0:17:05,000
that as space rapidly expanded,

409
0:17:05.26,000 --> 0:17:07,000
tiny quantum jitters from the micro world

410
0:17:07.26,000 --> 0:17:1,000
would have been stretched out to the macro world,

411
0:17:10.26,000 --> 0:17:13,000
yielding a distinctive fingerprint,

412
0:17:13.26,000 --> 0:17:15,000
a pattern of slightly hotter spots and slightly colder spots,

413
0:17:15.26,000 --> 0:17:17,000
across space,

414
0:17:17.26,000 --> 0:17:2,000
which powerful telescopes have now observed.

415
0:17:20.26,000 --> 0:17:23,000
Going further, if there are other universes,

416
0:17:23.26,000 --> 0:17:25,000
the theory predicts that every so often

417
0:17:25.26,000 --> 0:17:27,000
those universes can collide.

